# Multi-Expert Subagent Rule

Main Codex = orchestrator / integrator / final decision.
Subagents = expert parallel analysis, design, review; isolated implementation only when approved.

Before implementing a complex task, decide whether subagents are needed.

## When To Enable

| Scope | Rule |
|---|---|
| 1 module | Default single Codex |
| 2 modules | May enable relevant experts (analysis only) |
| 3+ modules | Must enable Multi-Expert Subagent |
| Agent/RAG | Must enable Agent/RAG Expert |
| Security / DB / dependency | Must enable Security & Quality |
| Frontend + backend API | Must enable Frontend + Backend + Integration Reviewer |

Use subagents if the task touches two or more of: frontend, backend, database, agent, rag, security, architecture, testing.

Not for: copy tweaks, single style fix, one field, simple validation, README one-liner.

## Parallelism Levels

- Level 1 — Parallel Analysis (safest, default for medium/large)
- Level 2 — Parallel Design (merge via Integration Reviewer)
- Level 3 — Parallel Implementation (rare: independent worktree, no file overlap, Context Pack ownership)

Analysis and design may run in parallel. Coding defaults to single-task.

Parallel implementation only if:

- tasks are independent
- allowed files listed in Context Pack
- no file overlap
- isolated branch or worktree per subagent
- Integration Reviewer merges and reviews final diff

For small tasks, use a single Codex flow.

Never allow multiple subagents to modify the same file without explicit integration planning.

Save reports under `docs/subagents/runs/RUN-YYYYMMDD-feature-name.md`.
